# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The **1998 World Youth Games** was an international multi-sport event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] More than 7,500 young athletes representing 140 countries of the world participated in this event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The Games took place in Moscow, Russia, from 11–19 July 1998.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The opening ceremony was held in Luzhniki Stadium (Стадион "Лужники").
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] It included 32 International Olympic Committee (IOC) members, 43 National Olympic Committee (NOC) presidents, Boris Yeltsin – then current president of the Russian Federation, Yuri Luzhkov – mayor of Moscow, with the presence of 80,000 spectators.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] Two Russian cosmonauts greeted all the spectators directly from Orbital Station Mir.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The mayor of Moscow and the IOC president addressed the spectators, and Boris Yeltsin declared the World Youth Games opened.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] Beginning from 2010, the Youth Olympic Games were to be held every four years in staggered summer and winter events complementing the Olympic Games, thus rendering the World Youth Games obsolete.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The motto of the World Youth Games was "the open world for childhood" and its mascot was Mishka (Мишка) – the Russian Bear that was also the mascot of the XXII Summer Olympic Games in Moscow 1980.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] On 27 November 1995, a small government delegation from Moscow visited the headquarters of the International Olympic Committee in Lausanne, Switzerland, in order to rally support for the organisation of a major international youth competition under IOC patronage in the Russian capital.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] Moscow's delegation argued that the city had a strong experience of staging sport events.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The IOC granted its patronage to the “World Youth Games” and an agreement was signed in April 1997 between the IOC, the city of Moscow and the Russian Olympic Committee, setting out the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] Athletes from 68 countries won 523 medals.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] After the agreement was signed, Moscow started its infrastructure preparations.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The first was the renovation of the Luzhniki Sports Arena, which was completed in September 1997 at Moscow's 850th anniversary.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The stadium was built in 1955, and in 1980 it became the heart of the XXII Summer Olympic Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The other major project was the construction of the Olympic village.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] This contraction was placed under the control of the city administration and it was based on the plan of the 1980 Olympic Village.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] The Village constituted of five 19-to-25 story buildings, a complex-sport gymnasium, a cycling track and a massive cafeteria.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] In addition, its landscape included artificial hills and a lake.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/1998-world-youth-games] Later, this complex-building became one of the most prestigious residential areas in the city.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The **1st Asian Indoor Games** were held in Bangkok, Thailand from November 12 to 19, 2005.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The sun is the symbol of the Olympic Council of Asia.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The redline, the blue line and the golden line forming like an "A" shape, together with a Thai roof, represent the Asian continent and the Asian Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The golden line that resembling Thai smile, expressing a warm welcome to visitors.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] Each sport discipline is animated with an elephant, thus giving the appearance of its cartoon movements in all events to be competed in the 1st Asian Indoor Games 2005.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] Children and other people alike will be fond of them, pleasant to look at them and keeping them for a souvenir after the end of the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] The blue and athletic elephant was named Hey and the yellow and plump one was Há.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] They were to convey the meaning of amusement, merriment and relaxation, thus in a way reflecting the natures of the Asian Indoor Games a great deal.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2005-asian-indoor-games] There are 37 Asian countries confirmed to participate in the game.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The **2007 Asian Indoor Games** (Chinese: 2007年亞洲室內運動會; Portuguese: *Jogos Asiáticos em Recinto Coberto de 2007*), officially known as the **2nd Asian Indoor Games** and also known as **Macau 2007**, were held in Macau, China from 26 October 2007 to 3 November 2007.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] Most events of the games took place at the Macao East Asian Games Dome.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The Emblem of the 2nd Asian Indoor Games gives an overall impression of the sun shining above the covered gymnasium.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] There were 44 Asian countries confirmed to participate in the games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] A total of 17 sports were scheduled to be competed in this edition of the Indoor Asiad.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2007-asian-indoor-games] The following is a list of the sports and the number of the designated events in parentheses.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] This was the last edition of the event to be held under the "Asian Indoor Games" name before it was merged with another Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) event – Asian Martial Arts Games to form the larger Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] The mascot of the 2009 event is the Ho chicken (*Gà Hồ*), a rare and distinctly Vietnamese breed of chicken.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] In Vietnamese culture, the chicken (particularly the rooster) have the five qualities of a man of honour: literacy, martial arts, physical strength, humanity and loyalty.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] All of OCA members participated in the Games, excluding: Pakistan, Palestine, & Timor-Leste.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] In the brackets are the total numbers of the athletes.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] The 2009 Asian Indoor Games did not feature indoor cycling, extreme sports and indoor hockey which were played in the previous games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-indoor-games] All of the demonstration sports in the 2007 Asian Indoor Games namely, 3 on 3 basketball, kurash and kickboxing, were included in this year's Asian Indoor Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] This event was the only Asian Martial Arts Games ever held, as four years later the event merged with another Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) event – Asian Indoor Games – to form the larger Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] The emblem comprises the letter "A" which stands for Asia that would include the Asian countries and population as well; while the letter "M" stands for Martial Arts Sports.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] The two connected letters are reflecting the meanings of modernity, activeness and simplicity; combining with the thoughts and cohesiveness of friendship and equality among the countries in Asia for the upcoming Martial Arts Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] For the overall picture, it is a mixture of contemporary art, manifesting that Thailand is to act as the host of the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Red is the main color of the OCA, reflecting the color of the fight, standing for the color of the heart and colorizing the Asian art.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Gold is the color of brightness of the Thai Kingdom and is the color for creativity and determination to organize the 1st Asian Martial Arts Games 2009.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] "Hanuman" is the Hindu Ape God considered to be the companion of the Hindu God Rama who has immeasurable fighting skills with strong determination.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] The Organizing Committee uses "Hanuman Yindee" as the Mascot as it wants to convey the message of the word "Yindee" which means proudness and gratification.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Furthermore, the Organizing Committee is using the word "Yindee" as to extend to everybody a warm welcome and a chance of making continuous friendship and solidarity throughout the entire peoples of Asia.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] 37 out of the 45 Asian countries took part.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Iran, North Korea, United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia and Timor-Leste did not compete.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Iran, a favourite for a spot at the top of the leader board pulled out of the contest after fears of catching swine flu forced the Iranian National Olympic Committee to advise the country pull out of the contest.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2009-asian-martial-arts-games] Palestine, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan did not have any competitors at the games but their athletes still counted in the draw in Taekwondo because of their late withdrawal.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The **2010 Summer Youth Olympics**, officially known as the **I Summer Youth Olympic Games**, and commonly known as **Singapore 2010**, were the inaugural edition of the Youth Olympic Games (YOG), an Olympic Games-based event for young athletes.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Held in Singapore from 14 to 26 August 2010, it was the first International Olympic Committee–sanctioned event held in Southeast Asia.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games featured about 3,600 athletes aged 14–18 from 204 nations, who competed in 201 events in 26 sports.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] No official medal tables were published, but the most successful nation was China, followed by Russia; host Singapore did not win any gold medals.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Most features that are unique to the YOG, such as mixed-NOCs teams (comprising youths from different countries) and the Culture and Education Programme (CEP), made their debut at the 2010 Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Although the concept dates back to 1998, formal plans for the YOG were only first announced at the 119th IOC session on 6 July 2007.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 21 February 2008, Singapore was selected as the host city after defeating Moscow 53–44 in a postal vote by 105 International Olympic Committee (IOC) members.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (SYOGOC) prepared eighteen competition venues and twelve training venues.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Float@Marina Bay hosted the opening and closing ceremonies and the Youth Olympic Village was located at Nanyang Technological University (NTU).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The committee also selected Games mascots Lyo and Merly (a lion and a female merlion), the Spirit of Youth emblem (through a design competition) and the theme song "Everyone", performed by five singers representing each major continent, combining North and South America.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Online media, Asian newspapers and 166 television broadcasters provided extensive coverage of the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The torch relay, which began on 23 July 2010, comprised a thirteen-day world tour of five cities, each representing a continent, and a six-day domestic leg.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Highlights of the opening and closing ceremonies include performances about Singaporean history and culture, a 32-metre (35 yd) Olympic cauldron, flags being brought onto stage and items featuring YOG symbols.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games were marred by discrepancies in the budget and attendance figures, two wrestlers caught doping, a walkover in the taekwondo final and allegations that Bolivian footballers were overage.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The concept of the YOG was developed in 1998 by Johann Rosenzopf in response to concerns over childhood obesity and declining youth participation in sports.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] IOC President Jacques Rogge formally announced plans for the YOG at the 119th IOC session in Guatemala City on 6 July 2007.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore, which had hosted the 117th session, made its first formal bid to host a multi-disciplinary sporting event of this magnitude.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Positive factors in its bid included its high connectivity with the world, its youthfulness as an independent country, and its positive reputation for excellence and multiracial harmony.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The city-state rolled out a high-publicity campaign which included being amongst the first to launch its official website, bid logo (despite IOC rules against bid logos) and a bid tagline "Blazing the Trail" on 16 October 2007.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It also got the local population to support its bid, including an effort by students to collect 1 million signatures.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Eleven cities expressed interest in hosting the Games, nine of which ultimately applied.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Five cities amongst the nine were selected for the shortlist: Athens (Greece), Bangkok (Thailand), Moscow (Russia), Singapore, and Turin (Italy).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The list was further shortened to two finalists, Singapore and Moscow.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 21 February 2008, Rogge announced that Singapore had won the postal vote 53–44 and was thus selected as the host for the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] There were concerns over whether two new venues that had been planned – a Youth Olympic Village and an equestrian complex – would be ready in time for the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A construction expert believed the US$423 million plan for an Olympic Village at the National University of Singapore (NUS) was feasible, and that the equestrian venue could be delivered on time.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In spite of the expert's findings, the Youth Olympic Village at the NUS's University Town did run into difficulties owing to increasing construction costs.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was subsequently decided that existing student halls of residence at Nanyang Technological University in Jurong West would be used for the Olympic Village.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (SYOGOC) was tasked with organising the inaugural Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was aided by a panel of advisors composed of Cabinet ministers and Senior Parliamentary Secretary Teo Ser Luck.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In addition, an Inter-Ministry Committee was established with Niam Chiang Meng, Permanent Secretary, Ministry of Community Development, Youth and Sports as its chairman.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore also received some international support for the Games preparations.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The People's Republic of China, host of the 2008 Summer Olympics, expressed its desire to assist Singapore in its preparations.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Sebastian Coe, Lord Coe, Chairman of the London Organising Committee for the 2012 Summer Olympics, announced that members of his organising team, including coaches and administrators, planned to attend the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Bid Committee secured 4,310 guaranteed rooms in 36 hotels.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The official hotel partner for the Games was Fairmont Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The IOC initially projected in 2007 that the Youth Olympic Games would cost US$30 million to stage.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore won its bid in 2008 with a budget of US$75.5 million (S$105 million) with strong government support.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The budget was later increased to U$284 million (S$387 million), thrice the original amount, which the organisers attributed to major revisions in the scope and scale of the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Costs were increased for logistics and transport, security, and upgrades of various sports venues and technology.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Financially, local companies received about 70%, or S$260 million, worth of contracts from the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Concerns over cost overruns were dismissed by SYOGOC Chairman Ng Ser Miang.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cost overruns was to become an issue that was raised by opposition parties during Singapore's 2011 general elections.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Eighteen competition venues were used at the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Events took place at 11 pre-existing venues, one new venue (the Singapore Turf Club Riding Centre), and six temporary venues that will be removed following the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Twelve venues were also set aside for training purposes.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Certain venues such as the Singapore Indoor Stadium and The Float@Marina Bay were temporarily converted to host sports events, while Kallang Field was upgraded to be able to host the archery competition.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Float@Marina Bay, a floating stage, was the main stadium for the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Capable of seating 25,000 spectators, it hosted the opening ceremony on 14 August, was a venue for the cycling event, and also hosted the closing ceremony held on 26 August 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] All competition and non-competition venues were within 30 minutes of the Youth Olympic Village, the Main Media Centre (MMC) and the Olympic Family Hotels (OFH).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] An Event Transport Operations Centre (ETOC) managed all transport matters relating to the YOG, providing real-time travel information.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A shuttle service linked all YOG venues for all accredited persons, who were also entitled to complimentary travel on public buses and the Mass Rapid Transit system.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Youth Olympic Lanes were designated along key routes for faster access to all YOG venues.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Youth Olympic Village (YOV) of the Games housed over 5,000 athletes and team officials for 18 days from 10 to 28 August 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Located in Nanyang Technological University (NTU), the YOV served as accommodation and a preparation point for the Games, and also hosted specially designed cultural and educational activities for athletes.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 7 June, it was announced that Parliamentary Secretary and SYOGOC advisor Teo Ser Luck, former national sprinter Canagasabai Kunalan and former national swimmer Joscelin Yeo had been appointed as the Village Mayor and Deputy Village Mayors respectively.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Plans for the Youth Olympic torch relay, dubbed the Journey of the Youth Olympic Flame (JYOF), were unveiled on 26 January 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The torch used was 60 cm (24 in) high, 5 to 8 centimetres (2.0 to 3.1 in) wide, and weighed 0.74 kg (1.6 lb).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The flame was lit at Olympia in Greece on 23 July 2010 and travelled to five cities representing the continents Asia, Africa, Europe, Oceania and the Americas.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] After spending 13 days on its world tour, the torch relay continued for another six days in Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A portable cauldron at the Marina Bay Promenade was lit by Minister Mentor Lee Kuan Yew on 13 August at the end of the torch relay in Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The opening ceremony of the Games was held on 14 August at The Float@Marina Bay, a floating stage near downtown Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Approximately 27,000 spectators attended the event, which took place against a backdrop of the city's skyline.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Event tickets cost between S$30 and S$200.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The show, the largest ever held by the city, involved over 750 hours of rehearsals.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Over 7,000 performers, mostly under the age of 18, took part in the ceremony.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] At the centre of the stage was the 32-metre (35 yd) tall Olympic cauldron designed by Randy Chan as a lighthouse.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was flanked by six giant LED displays, which stood behind a reflecting pool containing 200 t (7,100,000 oz) of water.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Prime Minister of Singapore Lee Hsien Loong was present at the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following pre-show warm-up and a countdown led by children and young drummers, the show began proper at 20:10 hrs (UTC+8)—a reference to the year of the event—with a fireworks show, followed by a cultural segment titled "*Selamat Datang*" that featured Chinese, Malay and Indian performers.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The segment ended with performances by homegrown artistes of Eurasian and Peranakan heritage, symbolising the mixture of tradition and modernity in Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Audience members were greeted with pre-recorded messages from several Olympic ambassadors: Olympians Usain Bolt, Michael Phelps and Yelena Isinbayeva, members of the band Thirty Seconds to Mars, and actors Jackie Chan and Jet Li.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] During the "Origins" segment on the city's history, performers entered the stage in freight containers to depict the arrival of the earliest immigrants.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The ceremony continued with a dance performance featuring popular songs from the 1940s to the present era.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A segment entitled "Monster" told the story of a young boxer who had to fight a giant monster.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He summons his Silat warriors to fight against the monster, but they failed, as well as when he summons his Kalari warriors and Wushu warriors.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] But soon he overcomes his inner fears and defeats the giant monster.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singer Seah Wei Wen then performed "Across The Finish Line" composed by Mayuni Omar & Mathilda D Silva, in the centre of the reflecting pool.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was followed by "Playing with Fire", which featured the dragon as a symbol of courage, strength and wisdom.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In this segment, 500 youth from Soka Gakkai Singapore participate to form from many fishes into a dragon.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Reflecting the theme of global co-operation, members of the World Youth Orchestra of the Singapore Games performed an orchestral piece featuring various instruments from around the world.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The orchestra was led by Darrell Ang, the young associate conductor of the Singapore Symphony Orchestra.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The following segment, titled "Bud", depicted rain as a symbol of hope and rejuvenation.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Ending the show segment of the ceremony were singers Marcus Lee of Ex-Dee and Lian Kim Selby, performing the song "A New Story", which was commissioned for the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Their performance was accompanied by a fashion show organized by students from LASALLE College of the Arts.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Each flag of the National Olympic Committees represented was brought on stage by an athlete representative.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following Olympic tradition, the flag of Greece entered first as the originator of the games, and the flag of Singapore entered last as the host nation.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The flag ceremony was followed by the singing of the Games theme song and remarks by Ng Ser Miang, Chairman of the Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee, and Jacques Rogge, President of the International Olympic Committee.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Games were then officially declared opened by S.R.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic Oath was taken on behalf of all athletes by Caroline Chew, on behalf of all judges by Syed Abdul Kadir, and on behalf of all coaches by David Lim Fong Jock.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Finally, a boat in the shape of a phoenix carried the Youth Olympic Flame across Marina Bay and was passed between six Singaporean youth athletes in a relay.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Sailor Darren Choy was the final torchbearer and lit the cauldron.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The 32-metre (105 ft) tall cauldron was designed by Dr.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tsai Her-Mann, a fellow and resident inventor of the Singapore Science Centre.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Designed to look like a lighthouse, its distinctive feature was a swirling 8 m (26 ft) column of fire dubbed the "vortex flame" or "fire tornado" inside a tube with an opening at the top end.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Hot air that could reach 300 °C (572 °F) created around the flame rose, drawing cool air upwards from openings in the base of the tower.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Just below the glass-panelled portion of the tower, the cool air was driven through angled guide vanes, thus creating the spiralling movement travelling upwards at 20 m/s (66 ft/s).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cauldron, which had been patented in Singapore and the United States, consumed about 2 MW (2,700 hp) of fuel, less than half the amount used by conventional Olympic cauldrons.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tsai said he hoped his design could be used for other Olympic events in future.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cauldron was secretly tested at 4:00 am during the two months leading up to the opening ceremony.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games featured 26 sports with a total of 31 disciplines and 201 events.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Within the 201 events, there were 8 mixed team events (Mixed-NOCs), 4 mixed team events (NOCs), 1 open event (Equestrian), 106 men's events, and 82 women's events.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] These included two disciplines under the IOC classification of aquatics (diving and swimming), and three under gymnastics (artistic, rhythmic and trampoline).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Each sport in the Games was represented by a pictogram inspired by the official "Spirit of Youth" emblem consisting of a red flame, a blue star and a green crescent, which was depicted participating in each of the 26 sports of the Youth Olympic Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The sport pictograms had a distinctive, contemporary graphic style that was intended to make them a highly recognisable feature of the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] About 3,600 athletes, aged 14 to 18, participated in the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] All 205 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) were represented, except Kuwait, which was suspended in January 2010 due to alleged government interference; however, three Kuwaiti athletes competed under the Olympic flag.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A unique feature of the YOG was the creation of the mixed-NOCs team event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To foster friendship among participants, teams were formed by athletes from different countries to compete on an intercontinental basis.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Mixed-NOC sports included equestrian-jumping, fencing, judo, modern pentathlon, and triathlon.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] There were eight events which composed entirely of mixed-NOCs teams, and as such all 25 medals in these events, including two bronzes in judo, were swept by mixed-NOCs teams.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The first gold medal of the Games was awarded to 18-year-old Japanese triathlete Yuka Sato, who won the girls' event on 15 August.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Host nation Singapore's first medal was a bronze in taekwondo for Daryl Tan on 16 August.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The first gold medal for a mixed-NOC event was awarded to team Europe 1, consisting of Yana Egoryan of Russia and Italians Marco Fichera Marco, Camilla Mancini, Leonardo Affede, Alberta Santuccio Alberta and Eduardo Luperi, which won the team competition in fencing.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The IOC set a vision for the YOG to be an event comprising a balance of sports, culture and education.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The objective of the Culture and Education Programme (CEP) that athletes participated in was to educate, engage and influence the athletes to develop true sportsmanship and to live by the Olympic values of excellence, respect and friendship, while having fun at the same time.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To promote cultural education among the participating youths, the YOG programme incorporated live youth performances, art installations and festivals revolving around the Olympics spirit and cultural diversity.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore's Youth Olympic Games Learning Centre is located at the SYOGOC headquarters along Kay Siang Road.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was officially opened by the SNOC President Teo Chee Hean and former pole vaulting champion Sergei Bubka on 30 October 2008.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The two-storey, 600-square-metre (6,500 sq ft) facility was open to the public for free allow visitors to discover and experience the spirit of the Olympics and trace Singapore's Games journey from winning the bid to host the first YOG in 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It featured several sections aimed at educating the public about different sports, as well as the history of Olympic records and the events lined up for the YOG.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The public could also try their hand at table tennis, fencing and basketball at interactive sections.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It subsequently closed for renovations from 18 August till the end of 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The closing ceremony of the Games was held on 26 August at The Float@Marina Bay.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The show began proper at 8pm Singapore time with youths, cheerleaders and the YOG mascots Lyo and Merly dancing to a medley of "Fame" and "Fight for This Love".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following the arrival of IOC President Jacques Rogge and Prime Minister of Singapore Lee Hsien Loong, 12-year-old Nathania Ong led the choir and the audience in singing the national anthem of Singapore.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In the next segment "Blazing the Trail", 5 young singers performed an upbeat song while students dressed to resemble the "Spirit of Youth", the Singapore 2010 emblem, performed a mass display item.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following the item, the athletes and the flags representing all competing nations made their way onto the floating platform.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A short clip showing the highlights of the games was then shown on the LED screens on the stage, accompanied by singer Heleyana-Ann Lachica Fernandez and a trio of musicians performing "A New Story".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Protocol segment followed the performances.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A tribute was made to the 20,000 volunteers who participated in the Games, with Singapore swimmer Rainer Ng making a short speech thanking the volunteers and eight other athletes presenting bouquets to eight representative volunteers.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] This was then followed by speeches from Ng Ser Miang, Chairman of the Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee, and Jacques Rogge, IOC President, with Mr.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Rogge officially declaring the Games closed in accordance with tradition.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic flag was then lowered with the singing of the Olympic Anthem.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In the handover ceremony, the Olympic flag was handed over from Teo Ser Luck, acting as the Mayor of Singapore, through Jacques Rogge, to Ji Jianye, Mayor of Nanjing, China, the host city of the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The national anthem of China was then played with the raising of China's flag, and a short video presentation showcasing Nanjing followed.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Youth Olympic Flame was then finally extinguished to the sounds of a flugelhorn.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A Celebration Concert marked the end of the show with songs and performances from local artistes.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Although the SYOGOC did not keep an official medal tally, news outlets, such as xinmsn, kept unofficial medal tables, where medals won by mixed-NOCs teams are credited to the NOCs that the athletes belong to.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The following table lists the top ten ranked NOCs and the host nation.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] See 2010 Summer Youth Olympics medal table for more details and a full table with medals won by mixed-NOCs teams counted separately.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games organisers used online media to market the event, including Friendster, Facebook, Twitter, WordPress and the official Youth.sg 2010 discussion forum.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Contracts were signed with 166 broadcasters to provide worldwide television broadcasts for the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] These include China Central Television, which telecast the opening ceremony live and has been screening nine hours of coverage each day on its CCTV-5 sports channel, and the Universal Sports television network in the United States.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In Canada, the games were broadcast by Canada's Olympic Broadcast Media Consortium, a joint venture between CTVglobemedia and Rogers Media.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Coverage of those games was limited to a one-hour daily highlights package on Sportsnet and TSN2 (rebroadcast several weeks later on TSN).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The consortium did not, however, own rights to the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics in Innsbruck.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The SYOGOC launched an international emblem design competition on 29 July 2008 through 29 August 2008 through its official website, requiring that the emblem incorporate the three themes of the Singapore identity, the Olympic ideals, and a youthful spirit.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The emblem competition for the Games attracted 1,500 participants, and the winning design entitled "Spirit of Youth" was unveiled on 10 January 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A contest to choose the official medal design for the first Youth Olympics was launched by the IOC in 2009.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] From November to December almost a hundred entries from 34 countries were received.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The mascots of the Games were Lyo and Merly, a fire-themed lion and a water-themed female merlion respectively.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The official theme song of the Games was "Everyone".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was performed by five singers representing six continents of the world, namely, Jody Williams (Africa), Sean Kingston (Americas), Tabitha Nauser (Asia), Steve Appleton (Europe) and Jessica Mauboy (Oceania).
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The executive producer of the song was local music producer Ken Lim.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The initial budget of 108 million SGD was exceeded over three times amounting to more than 300 million SGD.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The latter was denied by organisers, SYOGOC Chairman Ng Ser Miang saying: "[J]ust look at the faces of the children that are there, the sparkle in their eyes and the smiles on their faces.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Members of the public commented that although some events were sold out, there appeared to be many unoccupied seats at venues, and claimed that this was because the Ministry of Education (MOE) made a block purchase of 87,000 passes to be given to schools.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, students usually did not stay for the full duration of sessions, which can be up to seven hours long.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The MOE denied that students were to blame, stating that more than 95% of students allocated tickets had attended events, and that some schools had asked to purchase additional tickets due to overwhelming demand.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The SYOGOC announced that once sessions had begun, unoccupied seats would be resold to people who turned up in person at venues.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To enable venue managers to gauge the number of seats available for resale, teachers escorting students to events were instructed to inform venue managers if they intended to leave before sessions ended and the number of seats occupied by students.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 20 August, the organisers reported that tickets were sold out for all 26 sports except girls' football.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Controversy also arose from the YOG attendance policy in Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Primary School, a local primary school.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The school stated that a S$5 refundable deposit was required from students who attend the YOG events on a non-school day.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The principal, Clifford Chua, said that it was to "ensure that our children learn the value of responsibility and not take this rare opportunity for granted, by wasting the ticket and depriving others of the chance".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Also, the deposit was returned even if the child did not attend the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, the move garnered mixed reactions from parents, who either supported the idea or felt it was not the right way to do things.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Some other schools such as Nanyang Girls High School, Bukit View Primary School and Park View Primary School gave free tickets to their students while Anglo-Chinese School (Primary) encouraged co-pay of $1 to $2 by the students to teach them to treasure their tickets.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 16 August 2010, Iranian officials withdrew Mohammed Soleimani from the men's under-48-kilogram category taekwondo final against Israel's Gili Haimovitz, citing an ankle injury.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] According to the officials, Soleimani had first hurt his ankle at the World Junior Championships in Mexico earlier in the year, and the injury had flared up again during his semifinal contest against the US's Gregory English.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Soleimani was sent to hospital for an X-ray, and his ankle was put into a cast.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Haimovitz was awarded the gold medal by default at a victory ceremony at the Suntec International Convention Centre from which Soleimani, the silver medallist, was absent.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Interviewed later on, Soleimani said he was "very sad" to have missed the bout as he was "sure [he] was going to get the gold medal".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Israel's chef-de-mission Daniel Oren claimed that the pullout had been politically motivated.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He said: "It's not the first time this has happened at the Olympics.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To be honest, once our boy got into the final, we knew that this is going to happen.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] I spoke to our boy after the final and he, of course, was disappointed that he did not have a chance to win his gold through an actual fight.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He must have trained hard to get to this stage and was not given a chance to fight.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] We are dealing with sports here, youth sports, in fact.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It's a pity that politics got involved." However, IOC spokesman Mark Adams said: "As far as the IOC is concerned, there is no sinister intent here.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] What we know factually is that the athlete injured his ankle and was sent to the hospital for an X-ray.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tests revealed he did not suffer anything broken, and he is all right now.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] For us, that's the end of the story." Previously, Iran has stated that since its existing government does not recognize Israel as a state, its policy is to withdraw from competing against the country.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Arturo Garcia, chairman of the Coaches Association of Santa Cruz in Bolivia, told the Bolivian newspaper *La Razón* he had proof that at least five players in the Bolivian boys' football team had been over the age limit of 15 years.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Bolivia beat Haiti 5–0 to take the gold medal in the finals of the boys' football tournament on 25 August 2010.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Bolivian Deputy Sports Minister Miguel Angel Rimba ordered an investigation into the claim.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Montenegro coach Sava Kovačević, whose team was knocked out by Bolivia in the semifinals, said that Montenegro would ask football governing body FIFA to look into the matter.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, FIFA announced they would not be doing so as complaints concerning the eligibility of players should have been submitted in writing to FIFA's headquarters in Singapore at the Youth Olympic Games no later than five days before the first match, that is, by 8 August.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] FIFA also said that its staff had met all footballers individually at the Olympic Village and had checked their passports against their dates of birth provided by their respective National Olympic Committees.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Two wrestlers, Greco-Roman 50 kg silver medallist Nurbek Hakkulov of Uzbekistan and 63 kg freestyle wrestler Johnny Pilay of Ecuador, were disqualified on 15 October after testing positive for the banned diuretic furosemide.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It was the first event to be held under the "Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games" name following the merger of two OCA events – Asian Indoor Games and Asian Martial Arts Games, inherited the edition numeral of the former.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Doha, Qatar was initially scheduled to host the 4th Asian Indoor Games in 2011, but withdrawn in June 2008 due to "unforeseen circumstances", with the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) chose Incheon instead as a replacement and postponed the games to 2013.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The logo of the Games is a brush image of a Korean traditional 'Giwa' (Tile) Roof that resembles people – “人” (Hanja or Chinese character for "인" (In)) holding hands, the initial of Asia “A”, and the Incheon Bridge.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The wordmark ‘incheon 2013’ under the roof resembles the athletes from countries of the region that compete in various sports of the games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Similar to the Asian Games, the event's mascots were three spotted seals named Barame, Chumuro, and Vichuan and the event's motto was Diversity Shines Here.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Nine different venues were used for these Games: Most of the following would also be used for the 2014 Asian Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] All 45 member countries of the Olympic Council of Asia were invited to compete at these Games, with only 43 OCA countries taking pare in the 2013 games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] North Korea and Timor-Leste declined to send their athletes to these Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Indian athletes participated the Games under the Olympic flag because the Indian Olympic Association was suspended.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] A total of twelve sports were approved for the 2013 Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/2013-asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] What follows is a list of all the athletes that have tested positive for a banned substance during the Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The **Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games** (abbreviated as **AIMAG**) is a pancontinental multi-sport event held every four years among athletes from all over Asia.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] It is organised by the Olympic Council of Asia (OCA) and consists of Indoor and martial arts events with TV broadcasting potential, some of which were not contested at the Asian Games and Asian Winter Games Programs and are not Olympic sports.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The event is a merger of two formerly separate OCA-sanctioned events – **Asian Indoor Games** (abbreviated as AIG) and **Asian Martial Arts Games** (abbreviated as AMAG), first held in Bangkok, Thailand in 2005 and 2009 respectively.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Both events merged to form the present-day event in 2013, with the subsequent editions inheriting the edition numeral of the former.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] These Games are described as the second largest Asian multi-sport event after the Asian Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] In its history, five nations have hosted the Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games and sixty-three nations from Asia and Oceania and two teams have participated in the event.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The last Games were held in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan 17–27 September 2017, while the next edition are scheduled to be held in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia in 2026.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The Asian Indoor Games consisted of indoor sports with TV broadcasting potential, several of which are not included in the Asian Games and Winter Asian Games Programs and are not Olympic sports.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The sports program included electronic sports, extreme sports, aerobics, acrobatics, indoor athletics, dance sports, futsal, inline hockey, finswimming, and 25 metres short course swimming.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau also saw the first major test of FIBA 3x3, a formalized version of three-on-three basketball that saw its official worldwide debut at the 2010 Youth Olympics.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] FIBA 3x3 was also contested in the 2009 Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] Doha was given the rights to hold the fourth edition scheduled for 2011, but a year later, in June 2008, the Qatar Olympic Committee officially withdrew as host citing "unforeseen circumstances".
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] In response, the OCA said that the 2009 Asian Indoor Games would be the last edition of the games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The Asian Indoor Games and the Asian Martial Arts Games would then combine, becoming the quadrennial Asian Indoor and Martial Arts Games.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] The inaugural event was held in Incheon, South Korea in 2013.
[src:asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games/asian-indoor-and-martial-arts-games] All 45 countries whose National Olympic Committees are recognized by the Olympic Council of Asia and 18 countries whose National Olympic Committees are recognized by the Oceania National Olympic Committees.
